Fit Tip™: Sunday Shopping Secrets, Buying Organic! Let's first point out that the word "Organic" does not refer to the food itself, but how the food was produced. Now that we are clear on that let's save some money and learn which ones to buy Organic. Here, is a cheat-sheet of which fruits and vegetables to buy and not to buy Organic. The "Dirty Dozen" (Buy Organic) Yes, there are really 13: Apples, Strawberries, Peaches, Nectarines, Pears, Potatoes, Raspberries, Bell Peppers, Carrots, Celery, Grapes, Cherries and Greens (i.e.., Kale, Spinach, Lettuce). The following DO NOT HAVE to Be Organic: Asparagus, Avocados, Bananas, Blueberries, Broccoli, Cabbage, Cauliflower, Corn, Eggplant, Garlic, Kiwis, Mangoes, Onions, Papaya, Pineapple, Sweet Potatoes, Tomatoes, Shelling Peas, Watermelon.

Fit Tip™: Lose Weight with Chop Sticks? This maybe true. Replacing your fork with chop sticks is a simple way to slow down the eating process, while helping you to take in less food. It generally takes approximately 20-minutes for your brain to register if you're full, and using a fork is an easy way to overload your stomach. So, slow it down with chop sticks and avoid over-eating.

Fit Tip™: Break Your Negative "Food" Patterns. To create sustainable outcomes, when it comes to food, one must disrupt their negative patterns by interjecting positive new ideas. Try this for example, place a rubber band on wrist for the next 21-days. Every time you commit a food crime by ingesting soda, processed foods, sugar or high sodium based foods, or whatever may cause you to slip…you will transfer the rubber band to the other hand and start over for another 21-days. Your heightened awareness will help prevent faltering, distract negative emotions and keep you focused on a healthier eating path.

Fit Tip™: Buying New Shoes or Sneakers? Then, be sure to Buy at Night! Make shoe purchases in the evening when your feet are at their largest. Reason: Being on your feet can them to swell as the day progresses. So, purchasing a size 8 in the morning...maybe feeling little tight by days end.

Fit Tip™: Wintery Lips! To keep your lips from becoming Chapped, avoid licking them whenever possible. Reason: The saliva from your tongue wears off quickly, causing them to become more dry. This is an all too common experience with flavored Lip Balms or ones that have menthol. Instead, opt for a moistening lip balm that contains skin screen, natural oils or petrolatum.

Fit Tip™: Let Pumpkin Seeds 'Pump-Up'Your Shake! Just a 1/2 a cup of pumpkin seeds supplies a whopping 14grams of protein. And, if that's not enough of a health benefit…these crunchy little sees are a great source of magnesium. Studies have shown that individuals who frequently get migraines generally have low levels of magnesium. Increasing magnesium intake can help to reduce the number of migraines. So, be sure to sip up the health benefits of this seed in your next shake.

Fit Tip™: Give Your Sneaker a 'Twist'. With many people hitting the streets or trails for a run, I recommend digging deep into your closet and doing a little cleaning with your running sneakers. This may mean parting ways with your favorite kicks. However, this separation may help you avoid injury. A simple and effective way to know if your running sneakers have performed their last repetition is to perform the 'Twist Test". Simply, hold the sneaker at each end and twist. If the shoe easily rotates, the midsole is worn and indicates a replacement.

Fit Tip™: Make a Splash with the Sunday Fit Challenge! Turn a lazy summer day in the pool into a calorie-burning, high-intensity 60-Second Workout. Simply see how many repetitions you can perform of the following exercise. The exercise, Wall walkers: Stand approximately two feet away from the side of the pool. Fluttering hands in the water to keep body afloat, walk forward and then proceed up the wall as high as possible. Reverse direction and repeat. For more of this workout click the following link: http://www.shape.com/blogs/fit-list-jay-cardiello/summer-water-workout

Fit Tip™: Oh, My Aching Feet! Here's a simple and effective way to help treat and reduce the pain associated with Plantar Fasciitis. Simply, place a golf ball between the affected foot and floor. Begin, slowly rolling your foot over the ball. You can either sit to stand, while performing the action. Perform routinely at the start of and end of each day. You can follow with icing the bottom of the foot for 10-minutes afterwards.

Fit Tip™: Chia-Up Your Water. Stay hydrated this summer by adding Chia Seeds to your bottle of water. Being that these seeds are highly hydrophilic (meaning that they can absorb large amounts of water) they can help with hydration when outside temperatures begin to rise. Simply, add approximately 1.5 tbsp chia seeds into your bottle and watch these tiny seeds absorb up to 10 times their weight in water.

Fit Tip™: Got Knee Pain? They try shortening your stride. It really does not matter how cushiony the heel of your running sneaker is, the heel was not made to be landed on when running. It can lead to knee pain and make for an unenjoyable run. To help avoid landing on your heel, try shortening your stride. By shortening your stride you will land on the middle of your foot, which will help to activate your body's natural shock absorbers.

Fit Tip: Need a boost of protection in your protein shake? Try adding raspberries. As, this great tasting berry contains anthocyanins which can boost insulin production and assists in lowering blood sugar levels. Lowering your blood sugar levels will provide a strong defense against diabetes.

Fit Tip™: "STAY in BED" and Take the Sunday Fit Challenge! Begin in a traditional Pushup position with your hands in-line with your shoulders and resting firmly onto of mattress. Feet will be hip width apart and on top of bed. Brace core, bend elbows and lower body within 1-inch from bed. Quickly reverse direction. That's one repetition. Challenge Marks: 0-12 Repetitions (You need to make this part of your daily schedule); 13-25 (Showing some good strength); 26-35 (Your a Superhero); 36 or more repetitions and you have Superior Core Stability and Full Body Strength.

Fit Tip™: Crack Open Some Muscle! These quick and easy treats are staples to the any fitness meal regimen. They are loaded with approximately 5 to 6 grams of protein at the very low cost of only 60 calories per medium-sized egg. Move Monday: Holidays can add a lot of stress to your life. Especially, in your lower back. To ease lower back tension, while creating mobility throughout your hips - lay flat on your back with an inflatable ball or towel between knees. Arms extended at sides with palms down. Raise knees until they form a 90-degree angle, keeping shins parallel to floor. Keep lower back on floor and allow your knees to fall slowly to either side. Perform 30-60 seconds daily.

Fit Tip™: Listen Up Ladies! To help lessen those uncomfortable feelings associated with PMS...You may just want to avoid caffeinated beverages throughout your period. Reason: A study at the University of Oregon State found that the risk of PMS was up to SEVEN times greater in women who consumed just two or more cups of coffee or tea daily. Researchers felt that elevated levels of caffeine increased exhaustion, tension, anxiety and contributed to interrupted sleep patterns.

Fit Tip: Eat as if you're sick! It’s sad that whenever we, or a loved one, becomes ill, we then think to eat vegetables and fruit, get plenty of rest, and stay hydrated. All of your health solutions should be in your fridge, not your medicine cabinet. Stop waiting until you’re sick to become healthy. Start now, before it’s too late. And remember: The sooner a food can rot or go to waste, the better it is for you. That goes for processed foods from salty, cured meats to pantry items like potato chips or pretzels.

Bring your right knee to your right right elbow with your right foot pointed. Lower your knee down the length of your forearm from the elbow to the wrist. Return to start position and repeat on other side. Keep back flat and chin tall throughout the entire movement.

Fit Tip™ Got Cravings? Satisfy your Sweet Tooth with this simple step: Place a handful of grapes in a ziplock bag and let it sit in the freezer overnight. Fit Tip™: Save on Calories this Holiday Season by Cutting Your Dinner in Half! Restaurants can cause havoc for dieters. A simple way to stay focused with your diet is to ask your server to place half of your meal in a to-go when ordering and to deliver it when receiving the check. This will cut down on portion size, while keeping you from over-indulging.

Fit TIp™: Stay in Bed and Take the 60-Second Sunday Fit Challenge! See how many total repetitions of the following exercise that you can perform in 60-Seconds. The Exercise, T-UPS: Begin in a modified pushup position with hands directly under shoulders and knees bent on your mattress. Form a straight line from your head to knees. Brace core and extend right leg back until it becomes parallel to the bed. Bend elbows and lower upper body and hips to the mattress until chest is 1 inch off the bed. Quickly reverse the move. Repeat for 30 seconds, then switch legs. How many did you perform? Coach's Tip: Think of the three Hs when performing this move: head, heart, and hip. All should remain in one straight line throughout the entire movement.

Fit Tip™: Use Your T-Shirt to Check Your Training!
The seams of your shirt can be a good indicator of strength imbalances between your chest and biceps (anterior) and your back (posterior). Next time you’re wearing a t-shirt, stand in front of a mirror to see if the stitching from the neck to the shoulder forms a straight line (this a good indicator that you're incorporating proper posterior work). If the lines turn slightly inward from the neck to the shoulders (anterior tilt), you may want to focus more attention on developing your posture and back.

Lack of sleep may have you looking like Santa! Missing out on a few nights of rest can disrupt hormone levels, making you feel hungry even when your body doesn't need food.
The two hormones in your body that play an important role in controlling appetite and satiety are: Ghrelin, which stimulates appetite, causing you to eat and Leptin whose job it is to suppress appetite.
So, when sleep is restricted to a few hours a night, ghrelin levels go up and leptin levels go down...which can wreck havoc on body and might have you looking like Santa!

The 25 Moves of Christmas - Day 23. The Move, Knee Tappers. Start by sitting on the floor with your knees bent. Extend arms behind body with hands resting on floor. Drive palms and heels into floor, raising your body into a 'Bridge' position. Back should be parallel to the floor. Brace core and drive right knee as you reach your left arm toward navel. The knee and hand will unite above navel. Reverse direction and repeat with left knee and right hand. Continue alternating hands and knees as many times as possible in 60-Seconds.

Fit Tip™: Will Coffee Dehydrate You? The dehydration myth has long surrounded coffee for decades and its reputation as a diuretic is greatly exaggerated. Researchers at the University of Connecticut concluded that caffeine really had no influence on hydration status and that those who regularly drink coffee can develop a tolerance to potential diuretic effects of coffee. Noting that moderate consumption makes your urinate just a little more. The real issue with dehydration is that we are not drinking enough water. I recommend taking back half of your body weight in ounces of water a day.

Vacay Workout...with recovery built right in.
Benefits: Your bed offers a great place to get a quick workout in. Reason: training on an unstable surface like a bed, increases your proprioception which is basically the feedback loop between the body and the brain. You're training your brain to fire more rapidly to make adjustments to the body's position, based on circumstances such as the unstable surface. People think it's joint stability and core strengthening, and of course it is, but it's also the brain telling the body that we have to re-stabilize because what's under us is unstable.

Fit Tip: Fruit Makes You Fat? No! In all my years as a wellness professional, I have never had a client come to me overweight because they were eating too much fruit. These days, fruit has gotten a bad rap because of its sugar content. Yet, people forget to realize that fruit 'naturally' contains sugar. Unlike, many processed or made with fruit products that have sugar added in. Plus, fruit contains a host of nutrients as well as fiber, which helps slow your absorption of fructose, the main sugar in most fruits. And, please don't think that you can simply add a serving of Metamucil to a can of cola and make it healthy. Bottom line: Don't judge fruit by its 'natural' sugar content. Look at all its nutritional value fiber and all. And, remember you are not going to get fat eating fruit!

The 25 Moves of Christmas - Day 5: The Lunge Burnout. Begin in a tradition Lunge Position with your front knee forming a 90-Degree angle and back knee as close to the floor as possible. As lowest point, drive your front heel (as hard as possible) into the floor and hold for as long as you can... In proper position, you should be able to wiggle your front toes (This will allow you properly distribute weight on front heel without having your front knee role forward). Also, keep your chin parallel to floor and core tight. Once you can no longer hold the position, switch stances and begin with opposite foot forward.

Fit Tip™: Take the 60-Second Sunday Fitness Challenge. See how many repetitions of the following exercise that you can perform in 6-Seconds. The exercise, Scarecrow: Stand with your left foot on a pillow. Extend your arms out to the sides at shoulder height (again, like you're a scarecrow). Bend your right knee 90 degrees and raise it in front of you until your thigh is parallel to the floor (you should look like the Karate Kid!). Now, straighten and extend the right leg toward the floor until your toes almost touch the ground in front of you. Return to Karate Kid position and repeat as many times as you can, never letting your toes hit the ground. Repeat on the opposite side. Perform for 30-Seconds on each leg.

Fit Tip™: Stop Drinking Coffee before 9:30AM! I may get a lot of slack for that comment. But when it comes to Coffee. Timing is everything. Reason: The stress-related hormone, Cortisol has levels that are high around 8AM (when most of us drink our first cup), which means that your body is naturally caffeinating itself. So, it doesn't need coffee. Drinking your favorite cup of Joe during this heightened hour of Cortisol production may dull the effects of caffeine and cause a raised tolerance to caffeine later on. For, best results drink your first between 9:30-11:30AM when cortisol levels start to drop off.

The 25 Moves of Christmas - Day 14. Keep your Belly from looking like Santa with the Knee Scratcher: Begin in pushup position. Bring your right knee to your right right elbow with your right foot pointed. Lower your knee down the length of your forearm from the elbow to the wrist. Return to start position. Perform for 30-Seconds. Repeat on other side. Keep back flat and chin tall throughout the entire movement.

The 25 Moves of Christmas- Day 22. The Move, Pelvic Tilts (on all fours). Ease away low back stress after Holiday travel with this simple move. Start on all fours with your hands in-line with shoulders and knees hip-width apart. Take a deep breath in and tighten your abdominal muscles and tuck your glutes under as you slowly round your back. Exhale and allow your back to relax back to neutral position. Repeat slowly for 60-Seconds.

Fit Tip™: Headed on the Road this Holiday Weekend? Traveling can add a lot of stress to your life. Especially, in your lower back. To ease lower back tension, while creating mobility throughout your hips - lay flat on your back with an inflatable ball or towel between knees. Arms extended at sides with palms down. Fit Tip™: Is Lack of Sleep Causing Your Belly to Bulge? Skipping out on proper sleep can cause the bodies levels of Leptin to drop. The dropping levels of this hormone sends a message to the brain that there is a shortage of food and increases your appetite. This surge in appetite makes comfort food more appealing, causing you to over indulge in these types of foods. Do you body and waist a favor and make sleep an important part of your arsenal against high caloric comfort food.

Gain control of your mind by Practicing Misfortune.
Like an athlete, who puts him or herself through the worst of times in order to experience the best of times. We must constantly train our minds out of our comfort zones. Comfort is the worst kind of slavery because we fear that someone or something will take it away. Like a relationship or not having proper financial needs. But if you can not just anticipate it, but practice misfortune, then the chance of it disrupting your life will not be so feared.

Live on beans and rice for a month or spend only a few dollars a day. I'm not saying to give up your apartment and become homeless or end a relationship to feel pain.
But, put yourself face to face with what you dread. Seeing it will only decrease its strength, enabling you to gain control of your fear...which will ultimately enable you to control your thoughts and mind.

Fit Tip™: Ladies Listen Up! You Should Think Twice about Doing a Forward Lunge. This action exerts a lot of pressure on the joint. Fit Tip™: Hold the Sugar and Add a Date! Yes, I said Dates! These nutritious little guys can be a great alternative to sugar. Simply, remove the pits from the dates and soak for 15 minutes in hot water. Next, remove the dates from the water and place in a blender or food processor with a few tablespoons of water. Blend until you form a puree. Then, store the puree in the refrigerator and use as needed. This can be used in coffee, protein shakes or any baking recipe that calls for sugar.

Fit Tip™: "You Are NOT Sweating Out Toxins"! If you have been to a Yoga class, you might have heard the instructor mention the phrase 'You are Sweating Out Toxins". However, this statement is not 100% true. While, I am a huge proponent of Yoga and there are so many health benefits for those who practice it…sweating out Toxins is not one of them. Your body releases sweat in order to keep us cool and from over-heating. Eliminating 'Toxins' is naturally done via your liver, kidneys and digestive tract. Your best bet is enjoy all the benefits of Yoga and avoid ingesting toxins into your body.

Fit Tip™: Bug Bite? Put a Spoon on it...With summer comes bugs and with bugs come bites. To help relieve your next bug bite, simply place a metal spoon under hot tap water for 60 seconds. Experts state that the heat, which is transferred from the spoon onto your skin can help to destroy the protein that causes the allergic reaction. So, the next time you get a bite…put it the spoon to the test. ‪

Fit Tip™: Popcorn Knees! Are you one of the many who hear 'harsh' crackling sound coming from under your knee cap-whenver you workout? Well, you are not alone. You may be suffering from: Chondromalacia patella, which is the softening and breakdown of the tissue (cartilage) that lines the underside of the kneecap (patella). The condition is more common in females and many people do not even report feeling pain. If this sounds like you...Then try: Temporarily resting and stop all running. Instead opt for a bicycle ride or swim. Also, begin stretching your hamstrings and quadriceps. Physical therapy and a MD visit may help as well.

Fit Tip™: Will Coffee Dehydrate You? The dehydration myth has long surrounded coffee for decades and its reputation as a diuretic is greatly exaggerated. Researchers at the University of Connecticut concluded that caffeine really had no influence on hydration status and that those who regularly drink coffee can develop a tolerance to potential diuretic effects of coffee. Noting that moderate consumption makes your urinate just a little more. The real issue with dehydration is that we are not drinking enough water. I recommend taking back half of your body weight in ounces of water a day.

Fit Tip™: Got an Earache? Put some Garlic in it! Reason: Known as a Natural Healer. Garlic has antibiotic properties that help to fight bacterial infections. To benefit from its powerful healing power, try the following: Simply, add 1 to 2 cloves of crushed garlic cloves to a half of a cup of olive oil and warm it up slightly on your stove. Let it sit for a couple of minutes. Next, dip a cotton ball into solution and place over infected ear for a few minutes.

Fit Tip™: Take a 7-Day Positive Thinking Vacation. For the next 7-Days, aim to disrupt your negative pattern of thinking, by focusing on only positive solutions and outcomes. For example, whenever a negative thought or situation occurs, immediately focus on a positive solution or outcome. By focusing on doing what needs to be done in order to make the situation or thought better you will be keeping your mind in a positive building and constructive state. To help keep you focused on disrupting your negative thought patterns, wear a rubber band on your wrist. Every time you allow a negative situation or thought to overpower your thinking…place the rubber band on the opposite wrist and reset for another 7-Days.

The 25 Moves of Christmas - Day 18. The Move, Reaching Side Plank with Hold: Start in a side plank position with your left elbow placed inline with your left shoulder. Slowly reach to the ceiling with your right hand and hold. You want to form a straight line from your shoulders to your heels. Aim to see is you can hold this position for 30, or more seconds without lowering your hip. Then, switch sides and repeat the hold.

Fit Tip™: Remove a Splinter with a Banana Peel? Yes, this is TRUE! Bananas peels are 'loaded' with antioxidants, minerals, and vitamins, which make them the perfect natural cure for cell regeneration and ailments. For Splinters: Simply, cut out a small piece of the banana peel and wrap it over the area of your body (such as your finger) that has the splinter. Fit Tip™: Is Lack of Sleep Causing Your Belly to Bulge? Skipping out on proper sleep can cause the bodies levels of Leptin to drop. Do you body and waist a favor and make sleep an important part of your arsenal against high caloric comfort food.

Fit Tip™: Sore no more. It is believed that lemons have pain-relieving qualities, and thus can be ideal for post workout ache or for ailments suffered by those who sit behind a desk all day or are often cramped in cars and airplanes. I recommend squeezing three to four lemons and mixing in two to three tablespoons of honey into a small bowl. Honey has long been a side kick to lemon due to its antiseptic properties. Fit Tip™: A 'Cherry' a Day will Keep the Doctor Away? Cherries may soon be replacing the apple in this food folklore. Reason: Recently, researchers found that tart cherries contained the highest anti-inflammatory content of any food. This is great news for individuals who suffer from pain and stiffness associated with osteoarthritis, as well as athletes who use anti-inflammatory pain meds. Try adding in some into your daily meal plan. A recommendation of 1.5 cups of tart cherries daily will be sufficient.

Fit Tip™: Lack of Sleep May Be Making Your Belly Look Like Santa! Skipping out on proper sleep can cause the bodies levels of Leptin to drop. The dropping levels of this hormone sends a message to the brain that there is a shortage of food and increases your appetite. This surge in appetite makes comfort food more appealing, causing you to indulge in foods that you may otherwise enjoy. Do you body and waist a favor this Holiday season and make sleep an important part of your arsenal against high caloric comfort food.

Fit Tip™: Can't Sleep? Then, Switch to Purple Sheets! This color's tone is ideal for people who deal with sleep disorders as the color purple can actually encourage sleep and help you relax faster. Think about this the next time that you are shopping for bedding. Why is this important? Because a lack of sleep can cause you to crave sugar and carbs. Levels of leptin, a hormone that tells your brain that your full drops by 18%; while levels of ghrelin, which makes you crave comfort food increases by 28%. Plus, lack of sleep raises cortisol levels making your appetite surge. @shape_magazine

Fit Tip™: Don't Place Your Fitness over Your Health! Many people believe that fitness implies health, but this can be very far from the truth. As, one can appear physically dominate in the gym and still be of poor health. Health and Fitness and are meant to work together. Where one is about having the systems of your body working at optimal level, while the other is a focus on the ability to perform athletic like movement. When starting any Exercise Program, focus first on your health: sleeping better, changing your behavior, drinking water and adding produce to your diet. This will make your transition into fitness a 'SUSTAINABLE' one…instead of paying for a gym membership that you never use.

FIt Tip™: Sunday Fit Challenge. See how many repetitions of the following exercise that you can perform in 60-Seconds. The Exercise, Single Arm Burpee: Stand tall with feet hip-width apart, arms extended overhead and chin parallel with floor. Brace core and quickly squat down. Place your left hand on the floor in front of your feet, while right arm rests at your side. Once hips hit their lowest point, jump feet backward, bringing your body to a push-up position with feet slightly wider than hip-width apart. Jump feet back under hips, and jump hips and hands as high as possible toward the ceiling. Repeat, for 30-seconds using your left hand. Switch hands and continue using the right hand for an additional 30-Seconds.

Fit Tip™: Avoid using the Seat Pocket. Did you know that cold and influenza viruses can survive for hours on fabric and tissues? And people store everything from used tissues to chewed gum in the seat pocket. Plus, how many times do you think that airline instructional booklet or shopping guide has been sneezed or coughed on? Use the under-seat storage or toss your personal belongings into a large Zip-lock bag that you can place inside the seat pocket for protection.

Fit Tip™: Baked Potato Chips Are a Healthy Choice. Not! That is like stating that Diet Soda is a healthy beverage. The word ‘Baked’ has consumers believing that they are doing something good for their bodies when munching on potato chips. Sure, one ounce of baked potato chips may have 14% less calories and contain half of the fat. However, baked chips are more highly processed than their counter part and contain high levels of the cancer causing chemical acrylamide, which form when the potatoes are heated to high temperatures.

Fit Tip™: Popcorn Knees! Are you one of the many who hear 'harsh' crackling sound coming from under your knee cap-whenver you workout? Well, you are not alone. You may be suffering from: Chondromalacia patella, which is the softening and breakdown of the tissue (cartilage) that lines the underside of the kneecap (patella). The condition is more common in females and many people do not even report feeling pain. If this sounds like you...Then try: Temporarily resting and stop all running. Instead opt for a bicycle ride or swim. Also, begin stretching your hamstrings and quadriceps. Physical therapy and a MD visit may help as well.

Fit Tip™: Go 'Light' or Go 'Home'. You may never hear these words spoken in the gym. But, for many those words should be part of their workout vocabulary. With 111 Days till Summer, many guys will be working the Preacher Curl into the workout arsenal in an attempt to 'Pump' up their biceps. However, in hopes of getting Popeye popping bi-ceps they will overload the Ez-Bar achieving nothing more than bad form resulting in shoulder, forearm and lower back pain. Reason: In an attempt bulk-up, guys overload the bar with too much weight causing their shoulders to round over the pad, while their hips rise off of the seat. Instead, aim for 'Form' and go 'Light'. Start by adjusting the height of the seat such that your arm-pits rest near the top of the pad with your upper arms are placed in front of your upper body. Keep feet flat on the floor and avoid swinging or rounding your back at anytime throughout the lift.

Fit Tip™: Sunday Fit Challenge. Stay in BED and see how many of the repetitions of the following exercise you can perform in 60 Seconds: Money in Your Pocket. Begin in a traditional plank position with your forearms on the bed, shoulders aligned directly over your elbows, maintaining a straight line from your shoulders to your toes. From this position, dip your right hip to the bed. Return to the starting position and repeat on the left. Alternate back and forth as if you are tapping each pocket to the bed. Coach’s tip: Imagine that you are tracing an arch with your hips to ensure they do not rise above shoulder height.

Fit Tip™: Popcorn Knees! Are you one of the many who hear 'harsh' crackling sound coming from under your knee cap-whenver you workout? Well, you are not alone. You may be suffering from: Chondromalacia patella, which is the softening and breakdown of the tissue (cartilage) that lines the underside of the kneecap (patella). The condition is more common in females and many people do not even report feeling pain. If this sounds like you...Then try: Temporarily resting and stop all running. Instead opt for a bicycle ride or swim. Also, begin stretching your hamstrings and quadriceps. Physical therapy and a MD visit may help as well.

Fit Tip: Will Coffee Dehydrate You? The dehydration myth has long surrounded coffee for decades and its reputation as a diuretic is greatly exaggerated. Researchers at the University of Connecticut concluded that caffeine really had no influence on hydration status and that those who regularly drink coffee can develop a tolerance to potential diuretic effects of coffee. Noting that moderate consumption makes your urinate just a little more. The real issue with dehydration is that we are not drinking enough water. I recommend taking back half of your body weight in ounces of water a day.

Fit Tip™: The Power of the Color 'RED". This intense and powerful color will not only get your blood pressure rising, but also cause your appetite to go into high gear. And, most of America's popular-sit down and drive-through eateries have us all seeing red with their logos: Outback Steakhouse, Pizza Hut, KFC, Burger King, Wendy’s, Sonic, Dairy Queen, Arbys, Chili’s…the list goes on. I’d guess that the brand managers deliberately used the color red to lure people into their restaurants and make them eat, and eat and eat. So, don’t fall prey! However, since observing the color red can cause an energy surge, you can benefit from wearing red clothes while exercising, or performing your routine on a Red Yoga Mat. Better yet, paint the walls of your in-home gym a vibrant red to get the most of your workouts.

Fit Tip™: Take the 60-Second Sunday Fit Challenge. See how many repetitions of the following exercise that you can perform in 60-Seconds. The Breakdancer: Start on all fours. In one swift movement, swing your left leg under your hips and extend it fully to the ceiling. Upon driving your left leg under your hip, simultaneously reach your right hand towards the ceiling and have the left foot and right hand meet at their highest points. Retract back to your original starting position and repeat on the other side. Do as many reps as you can for 60-Seconds.

Fit Tip™: Coffee Lovers Listen Up! Besides kick starting your day, coffee is one of the greatest sources of antioxidants in the American diet. Research has suggested that both caffeinated and decaffeinated coffee may help protect against heart disease, Parkinson's disease, colon cancer and type 2 diabetes. Also, the smell of coffee has been shown to reduce stress when sleep deprived. So, the next time your find yourself feeling groggy and unhappy after only catching a few hours of sleep…try walking into your favorite coffee shop and let the aroma lift your mood.

Fit Tip™: What Does the word 'Natural' Mean? Actually, 'NOTHING'!!! The FDA has not provided a real definition for this food labeling term. Yet, most consumers feel that they are purchasing a 'Healthier' and 'Safer' product when they see the word Natural on the label. What to do? Don't be mislead by brands that use this labeling…Especially, on products for your children. Instead, opt for whole fruits and vegetables, or call the brand and inquire what the ingredients are that being proclaimed as Natural.
